06006nam a22006615i 9780773562998DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19921992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735629987 a10.1515/97807735629982doi  a(DE-B1597)655003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD82 ǂb E62 1992eb 7aPOL0240002bisacsh04a338.91 aSavoie, Donald J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEquity and Efficiency in Economic Development :bEssays in Honour of Benjamin Higgins /cIrving Brecher, Donald J. Savoie. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (448 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tConcepts -- tEquity and Efficiency in Development: Basic Concepts -- tDevelopment, Equity, and Liberation -- tFacts -- tDevelopment, Efficiency, and Equity in Historical Perspective -- tEquity and Efficiency in the 1 “Mature” Socialist Society, the USSR -- tWhat Is the Evidence on Income Inequality and Development? -- tPolicy -- tFiscal Equity and Economic Development -- tThe Status and Efficiency of Regional Development Policies -- tRegional Policies for Equity: Can They Be Justified? -- tEquity, Efficiency, and the Managerial Paradigm -- tHunger -- tThe Overexpansion of Higher Education in the Third World -- tInternational Aspects -- tNew Directions in Canada’s Foreign Aid? The Winegard Report and Beyond -- tThe Static Welfare Economics of Foreign Aid: A Consolidation -- tTrade Restrictions versus Foreign Aid As a Means of Improving a Country’s Welfare -- tThe Underdevelopment of Development -- tTowards a New Paradigm? Two Views -- tSelected Works of Benjamin Higgins -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ideological foundations of the contributors range from personalized neo-Marxism, through "extreme centre" neo-Keynesianism, to hard-line neoclassical mathematical economics. Despite this diversity there is a surprising degree of consensus. No contributor advocates centralized planning and none expects a free market to cure all economic ills. Opinions vary as to how well the market actually works, but all agree that equity and efficiency are essential goals which most consider to be complementary rather than mutually exclusive. In the concluding chapter it is suggested that current economic problems are caused not so much by government intervention as by the nature of that intervention. The authors believe that the recent ideological convergence may lead to a new paradigm, a theory of the optimal blend of market and management that will be flexible enough to deal with the varying conditions of diverse societies, thus simplifying the task of creating a smooth-running global economy. The contributors are Irma Adelman, Mark Blaug, Kenneth Boulding, Irving Brecher, Albert Breton, John S. Chipman, André Gunder Frank, Martha Fuentes Frank, Niles Hansen, Murray C. Kemp, Robin Marris, Richard Musgrave, Walt Rostow, Donald J. Savoie, Nicholas Spulber, and Paul Streeten. Higgins himself contributes a chapter on basic concepts and collaborates with Donald Savoie on the final chapter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aAdelman, Irma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlaug, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulding, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrecher, Irving, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBrecher, Irving, econtributor.4ct